---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import BoundaryDesigner from '../components/BoundaryDesigner.tsx';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Step 5: Bound" step={5} prev={`${base}4-map/`} next={`${base}6-pilot/`}>
  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto py-10 px-4 landing-content">

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h1>Reality check</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">You have a design. Now stress-test it. What can go wrong, what must stay off-limits and what decisions do you need to make before building anything?</p>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>Why this step matters</h2>

      <p>
        The Map page produced an ideal design. This page puts the brakes on it. Every AI component can fail in specific ways. Every dataset has privacy constraints. Every model has a cost. And some errors are acceptable while others are not.
      </p>

      <p>
        The goal is not to be cautious. It is to be specific. By the end of this page, you should know exactly what you need to protect against and how.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="mb-10" id="bound-tabs">
      <div class="tab-bar">
        <button class="tab-btn active" data-tab="errors">Error tolerance</button>
        <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="data">Data and privacy</button>
        <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="cost">Cost</button>
        <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="humans">Human checkpoints</button>
      </div>

      <div class="tab-panel active" id="tab-errors">
        <p>Not all errors are equal. A slightly off tone in a LinkedIn post is fixable. A wrong number in a board deck is not. Think about what happens when each part of your system produces a bad output.</p>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Errors in generated text</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>Language models <a href="https://casmi.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2024/the-hallucination-problem-a-feature-not-a-bug.html">hallucinate</a>. They produce text that sounds right but can be factually wrong. This is not a bug that will be fixed. It is how the technology works.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> Who sees this output? Is it a draft or a final product? What happens if it contains a factual error?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Errors in numbers</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>Numbers from a spreadsheet are deterministic and reliable. Numbers from an LLM are not. An LLM can generate a number that looks calculated but is actually made up. A wrong projection in a brainstorming session is tolerable. A wrong revenue figure in a board report is not.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> Does any AI component produce or handle numbers? Are those numbers verified against a deterministic source?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Errors in retrieved information</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>If your design uses retrieval (RAG), the answers are only as good as the documents indexed. Stale documents produce stale answers. A citation does not guarantee the interpretation is correct.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> How current are the source documents? What happens if the system retrieves the wrong document?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Errors in signals and patterns</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>If your design surfaces signals from unstructured data, these are pattern matches, not facts. The system might count wrong, misattribute a mention or flag something irrelevant.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> Are signals clearly labelled as signals, not facts? What is the worst that happens if a signal is wrong?</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>

      <div class="tab-panel" id="tab-data">
        <p>Most AI models run in the cloud. That means your data is sent to an external server for processing. For some workflows this is fine. For others it is a dealbreaker.</p>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Cloud vs local models</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>Cloud models (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google) are the most capable but your data leaves your infrastructure. Local models (Ollama, llama.cpp) keep everything on your machines but require hardware and expertise. For many tasks, a smaller local model works well enough.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> What data does each AI component process? Is any of it confidential, personal or regulated?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Access control and permissions</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>If your system retrieves from internal sources, it must respect existing permissions. A system that surfaces salary data or confidential client information to the wrong person is worse than no system at all.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> Who can see what in the current workflow? Does the AI system enforce the same permissions?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Hard rules</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>Every system needs things it must never do regardless of what the AI decides. These should be enforced in the architecture, not just documented in a policy.</p>
            <p>Examples: never send an email without human approval. Never modify financial records. Never surface confidential documents to unauthorised users.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>

      <div class="tab-panel" id="tab-cost">
        <p>Not every step needs the most expensive model. And what costs pennies at pilot scale can cost thousands at full scale.</p>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Model selection</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>A step that classifies support tickets might work with a small, cheap model. A step that drafts nuanced board commentary might need a more capable one. Match the model to the task.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> For each AI component, what is the simplest model that could work? Have you tested smaller models?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Cost at scale</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>Deterministic components (rules, APIs, calculations) are effectively free at scale. LLM calls are not. Think about volume before you build.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> How often will each AI component be called? What is the cost at pilot vs full scale?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Environmental cost</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>AI systems <a href="https://www.technologyreview.com/2023/12/05/1084417/ais-carbon-footprint-is-bigger-than-you-think/">consume significant energy</a> and <a href="https://www.unep.org/news-and-stories/story/ai-has-environmental-problem-heres-what-world-can-do-about">massive amounts of water</a>. <a href="https://www.npm.org/2024/07/12/g-s1-9545/ai-brings-soaring-emissions-for-google-and-microsoft-a-major-contributor-to-climate-change">Running models at scale has a real footprint</a>. Using a large model for a task a script could handle is wasteful.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> For each AI component, is a model call actually necessary? Could a rule, a template or a script do it instead?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

      </div>

      <div class="tab-panel" id="tab-humans">
        <p>Not everything needs to pause for human approval. But some things absolutely do. The question is which ones.</p>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Approval gates</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>An approval gate pauses the workflow until a person signs off. Use these for high-stakes outputs: anything customer-facing, legally binding or financially significant.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> Which outputs need human approval? Who approves? What happens if they are unavailable?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Monitoring vs approval</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>Low-stakes outputs can proceed with monitoring: the system logs everything and a person reviews periodically. If you put approval gates on everything, the human becomes a bottleneck and starts rubber-stamping.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> Which outputs need approval and which can proceed with monitoring?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Rejection paths</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>If the reviewer rejects the AI output, what happens? Does it regenerate? Does a person handle it manually? Does it queue?</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> For each approval gate, what is the fallback when the human disagrees?</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="bound-section">
          <summary>Bias and transparency</summary>
          <div class="bound-detail">
            <p>Models reflect <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07856-5">biases in their training data</a>. If your system makes decisions that affect people, test for this. <a href="https://hdsr.mitpress.mit.edu/pub/aelql9qy">Users should know when they are interacting with AI</a>.</p>
            <p><strong>Think about:</strong> Does your system produce outputs that affect people? Is it clear to users when AI is involved?</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>

      <script is:inline>
        document.querySelectorAll('.tab-btn').forEach(function(btn) {
          btn.addEventListener('click', function() {
            var tabId = this.getAttribute('data-tab');
            document.querySelectorAll('.tab-btn').forEach(function(b) { b.classList.remove('active'); });
            document.querySelectorAll('.tab-panel').forEach(function(p) { p.classList.remove('active'); });
            document.querySelector('[data-tab="' + tabId + '"]').classList.add('active');
            document.getElementById('tab-' + tabId).classList.add('active');
          });
        });
      </script>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>Your boundary decisions</h2>

      <p>
        Based on your design, here are the specific decisions you need to make. For each item, record how you are handling it. These decisions will feed into your pilot plan.
      </p>

      <BoundaryDesigner client:load />
    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .landing-content .subtitle {
    color: var(--text-light);
    font-size: 15px;
  }

  .tab-bar {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    overflow: hidden;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .tab-btn {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 0.625rem 0.5rem;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-family: inherit;
    cursor: pointer;
    border: none;
    border-right: 1px solid var(--border);
    background: #fff;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    transition: all 0.15s;
  }

  .tab-btn:last-child {
    border-right: none;
  }

  .tab-btn.active {
    background: var(--purple);
    color: #fff;
  }

  .tab-btn:hover:not(.active) {
    background: #fafafa;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .tab-panel {
    display: none;
  }

  .tab-panel.active {
    display: block;
  }

  .tab-panel > p {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .bound-section {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .bound-section summary {
    padding: 0.875rem 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 15px;
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
  }

  .bound-section summary::after {
    content: '+';
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-weight: 400;
  }

  .bound-section[open] summary::after {
    content: '\2212';
  }

  .bound-section summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .bound-detail {
    padding: 0 1.25rem 1.25rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding-top: 1rem;
  }

  .bound-detail p {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .bound-detail p + p {
    margin-top: 1.25em;
  }
</style>
